 {"id":"bd-1pl","title":"Implement back_populates bidirectional relationship sync","description":"# Task: Implement back_populates Bidirectional Relationship Sync

## Context
When you set hero.team = some_team, the team.heroes should automatically include hero. This is the "back_populates" feature from SQLAlchemy/SQLModel.

## The Problem Without back_populates
```rust
let mut hero = Hero::new("Spider-Man");
let mut team = Team::new("Avengers");

hero.team = Related::loaded(team.clone());

// BUG: team.heroes is still empty!
// The relationship is one-directional only.
assert!(team.heroes.is_empty());  // Fails user expectations
```

## The Solution With back_populates
```rust
// Both sides are defined with back_populates
#[derive(Model)]
struct Hero {
    #[sqlmodel(relationship(model = "Team", back_populates = "heroes"))]
    team: Related<Team>,
}

#[derive(Model)]  
struct Team {
    #[sqlmodel(relationship(model = "Hero", back_populates = "team"))]
    heroes: RelatedMany<Hero>,
}

// Now when you set one side...
hero.set_team(&team);  // Generated method

// ...the other side is automatically updated
assert!(team.heroes.iter().any(|h| h.id == hero.id));  // ✓
```

## What to Implement

### 1. Relationship Setter Methods
Generate setter methods that handle bidirectional sync:
```rust
// Generated by macro for Hero
impl Hero {
    /// Set the team relationship with bidirectional sync.
    pub fn set_team(&mut self, team: &Team) {
        // Set forward direction
        self.team = Related::loaded(team.clone());
        self.team_id = team.id;

        // Set reverse direction (back_populates)
        // This is tricky - need mutable access to team
        // Option 1: Clone and modify (expensive)
        // Option 2: Use interior mutability (RefCell)
        // Option 3: Require mutable team parameter
    }

    /// Clear the team relationship.
    pub fn clear_team(&mut self) {
        // Remove from team.heroes if was set
        if let Some(old_team) = self.team.get() {
            // How to modify old_team.heroes?
        }
        self.team = Related::empty();
        self.team_id = None;
    }
}
```

### 2. Interior Mutability Approach
Use RefCell or similar for relationship fields:
```rust
pub struct Related<T: Model> {
    fk_value: Option<Value>,
    loaded: RefCell<Option<T>>,  // Interior mutability
}

pub struct RelatedMany<T: Model> {
    parent_pk: Option<Value>,
    loaded: RefCell<Vec<T>>,     // Interior mutability
}

// Now we can modify even through shared references
impl<T: Model> RelatedMany<T> {
    pub fn push(&self, item: T) {
        self.loaded.borrow_mut().push(item);
    }

    pub fn remove_by_pk(&self, pk: &Value) {
        self.loaded.borrow_mut().retain(|i| i.pk() != pk);
    }
}
```

### 3. Session-Aware Approach (Preferred)
Better: Do sync through Session, which tracks all objects:
```rust
impl Session {
    /// Set a relationship with automatic back_populates sync.
